	abstract = {The Henderson apparatus was used to expose mice to aerosols of Mycobacterium tuberculosis (H37Rv), M. kansasii (strain P1), another photochromogenic mycobacterium (P8), and two strains of nonphotochromogenic mycobacteria (T-39 and P2). Organisms were enumerated in the bacterial slurries before and after nebulization in a Collison nebulizer, in air samples from the equipment during nebulization, and in the lungs of animals killed at various intervals after exposure. A Goldberg rotating drum was used to test the ability of the organisms to survive aerial suspension.

